#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:10
msgid "4.2 Restricted Boltzmann Machine (RBM)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:12
msgid ""
"The classic Boltzmann machine, as presented in Section [4.1 The Classic "
"Boltzmann Machine: Visible and Hidden Symmetry](/kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-overall), is theoretically "
"powerful but computationally intractable due to the need for equilibrium "
"sampling over a fully connected graph. The <b>Restricted Boltzmann "
"Machine (RBM)</b>, introduced by Paul Smolensky in 1986 under the name "
"<em>Harmonium</em> and later popularized by Geoffrey Hinton, imposes a "
"simple but profound architectural constraint that dramatically reduces "
"sampling complexity while preserving the ability to model complex "
"probability distributions. This section details the RBM architecture, its"
" mathematical properties, and why it has become the workhorse of energy-"
"based unsupervised learning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:14
msgid "<b>The Architectural Restriction: A Bipartite Graph</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:16
msgid ""
"The defining characteristic of an RBM is its <b>restricted "
"connectivity</b>: the network is organized as a <b>bipartite graph</b> "
"with two layers, a visible layer and a hidden layer. Connections exist "
"<b>only</b> between visible and hidden units. There are <b>no visible-"
"visible connections</b> and <b>no hidden-hidden connections</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:18
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Formally, let the visible units be $\\mathbf{v} = (v_1, v_2, \\ldots, "
"v_{N_v})$ with biases $\\mathbf{b} = (b_1, \\ldots, b_{N_v})$, and the "
"hidden units be $\\mathbf{h} = (h_1, h_2, \\ldots, h_{N_h})$ with biases "
"$\\mathbf{c} = (c_1, \\ldots, c_{N_h})$. The weight matrix $\\mathbf{W}$ "
"is of size $N_v \\times N_h$, where $w_{ij}$ connects visible unit $i$ to"
" hidden unit $j$. There is no weight matrix for visible-visible or "
"hidden-hidden pairs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:20
msgid "This restricted topology is illustrated below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:22
msgid ""
"This restricted topology yields a crucial property: <b>conditional "
"independence</b>. Given the visible units, the hidden units become "
"independent of each other. Conversely, given the hidden units, the "
"visible units become independent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:24
msgid "<b>Energy Function and Joint Distribution</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:26
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The energy of a joint configuration $(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})$ in an "
"RBM with binary visible and binary hidden units is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:28
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = -\\sum_{i=1}^{N_v} b_i v_i - "
"\\sum_{j=1}^{N_h} c_j h_j - \\sum_{i=1}^{N_v} \\sum_{j=1}^{N_h} v_i "
"w_{ij} h_j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:30
msgid "In matrix notation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:32
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = -\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{v} - "
"\\mathbf{c}^\\top \\mathbf{h} - \\mathbf{v}^\\top \\mathbf{W} \\mathbf{h}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:34
msgid ""
"The joint probability distribution is, as always, given by the Boltzmann "
"distribution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:36
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\exp\\left(-E(\\mathbf{v}, "
"\\mathbf{h})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:38
msgid "with the partition function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:40
msgid ""
"Z = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}, \\tilde{\\mathbf{h}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E(\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}, \\tilde{\\mathbf{h}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:42
msgid "<b>Probability Distributions in RBMs</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:44
msgid ""
"To better understand the generative and training processes of an RBM, we "
"need to clearly distinguish several key probability distributions. All of"
" them originate from the joint distribution $p(v, h)$, but they differ in"
" their normalization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:46
msgid "<b>Joint distribution </b>$p(v, h)$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:48
#, python-brace-format
msgid "p(v, h) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\exp(-E(v, h))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:50
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $Z = \\sum_{v,h} \\exp(-E(v, h))$. This is the most complete "
"description of the model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:52
msgid "<b>Marginal distribution </b>$p(v)$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:54
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This is the distribution we care most about. Because it directly defines "
"the probability that the RBM assigns to observed visible data (e.g., "
"images, features) without reference to the hidden units. During training,"
" our goal (maximum likelihood estimation) is to maximize $p(\\mathbf{v})$"
" over the training data. A well-trained RBM should be able to sample new "
"visible configurations from $p(\\mathbf{v})$ that look like real data. "
"The hidden units are latent auxiliary variables that capture complex "
"dependencies, but $p(\\mathbf{v})$ is the ultimate evaluation criterion "
"for the generative quality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:56
msgid "It is obtained by summing over all possible hidden unit states:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:58
msgid "p(v) = \\frac{\\sum_{h} \\exp(-E(v, h))}{Z}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:60
msgid ""
"This is the distribution we care most about because it directly defines "
"the probability that the RBM assigns to observed visible data (e.g., "
"images, features) without reference to the hidden units. During training,"
" our goal is to maximize $p(v)$ over the training data. Ideally, a well-"
"trained RBM should be able to sample new visible configurations from "
"$p(v)$ that look like real data. The hidden units only serve as latent "
"auxiliary variables to capture complex dependencies, but $p(v)$ is the "
"ultimate evaluation criterion for the generative quality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:62
msgid "<b>Conditional probabilities</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:64
msgid ""
"These are the key to the computational efficiency of RBMs. Due to the "
"bipartite structure, they factorize into products of independent "
"Bernoulli distributions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:65
msgid ""
"<b>Distribution of hidden units given visible units </b>$p(h|v)$: $$  "
"p(h|v) = \\frac{p(v, h)}{p(v)} = \\frac{\\exp(-E(v, h))}{\\sum_{h'} "
"\\exp(-E(v, h'))}$$ Because there are no hidden-hidden connections in an "
"RBM, this distribution factorizes as  $$p(\\mathbf{h} \\mid \\mathbf{v}) "
"= \\prod_{j=1}^{N_h} p(h_j \\mid \\mathbf{v}),$$ where $p(h_j = 1 \\mid "
"\\mathbf{v}) = \\sigma\\left( c_j + \\sum_{i} w_{ij} v_i \\right)$ , "
"enabling parallel sampling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:71
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Distribution of visible units given hidden units </b>$p(v|h)$: "
"Similarly, we have $$p(\\mathbf{v} \\mid \\mathbf{h}) = "
"\\prod_{i=1}^{N_v} p(v_i \\mid \\mathbf{h})$$ where $p(v_i = 1 \\mid "
"\\mathbf{h}) = \\sigma\\left( b_i + \\sum_{j} w_{ij} h_j \\right)$"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:75
msgid "<b>The Key Computational Advantage: Conditional Independence</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:77
msgid ""
"The absence of intra-layer connections yields a crucial property: "
"<b>conditional independence</b>. Given the visible units, the hidden "
"units become independent of each other. Conversely, given the hidden "
"units, the visible units become independent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:79
msgid ""
"Mathematically, the conditional probability of a hidden unit $h_j$ being "
"active given the visible layer is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:81
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(h_j = 1 \\mid \\mathbf{v}) = \\sigma\\left( c_j + \\sum_{i=1}^{N_v} "
"w_{ij} v_i \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:83
msgid ""
"where \\( \\sigma(z) = 1/(1 + \\exp(-z)) \\) is the sigmoid function. "
"Because there are no hidden-hidden connections, the joint conditional "
"distribution over all hidden units factorizes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:85
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{h} \\mid \\mathbf{v}) = \\prod_{j=1}^{N_h} P(h_j \\mid "
"\\mathbf{v})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:87
msgid ""
"Similarly, the conditional probability of a visible unit being active "
"given the hidden layer is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:89
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(v_i = 1 \\mid \\mathbf{h}) = \\sigma\\left( b_i + \\sum_{j=1}^{N_h} "
"w_{ij} h_j \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:91
msgid ""
"and the visible units are conditionally independent given the hidden "
"units:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:93
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{v} \\mid \\mathbf{h}) = \\prod_{i=1}^{N_v} P(v_i \\mid "
"\\mathbf{h})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:95
msgid "<b>Efficient Gibbs Sampling: Block Updates</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:97
msgid ""
"The conditional independence property transforms Gibbs sampling from a "
"slow, unit-by-unit process into a fast, <b>block-wise</b> process. A "
"single round of Gibbs sampling consists of two parallel steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:99
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Sample hidden layer given visible layer</b>: For each hidden unit $j$,"
" compute $P(h_j = 1 \\mid \\mathbf{v})$ and sample $h_j \\in \\{0,1\\}$ "
"accordingly. All hidden units can be sampled simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:100
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Sample visible layer given hidden layer</b>: For each visible unit "
"$i$, compute $P(v_i = 1 \\mid \\mathbf{h})$ and sample $ v_i \\in "
"\\{0,1\\}$. All visible units can be sampled simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:102
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This pair of steps constitutes one full step of <b>block Gibbs "
"sampling</b>. Starting from a visible vector $\\mathbf{v}^{(0)}$, the "
"sequence is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:104
msgid ""
"\\mathbf{v}^{(0)} \\xrightarrow{P(\\mathbf{h} \\mid \\mathbf{v}^{(0)})} "
"\\mathbf{h}^{(0)} \\xrightarrow{P(\\mathbf{v} \\mid \\mathbf{h}^{(0)})} "
"\\mathbf{v}^{(1)} \\xrightarrow{P(\\mathbf{h} \\mid \\mathbf{v}^{(1)})} "
"\\mathbf{h}^{(1)} \\rightarrow \\cdots"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:106
msgid ""
"Each half-step updates an entire layer in parallel, making the RBM vastly"
" more efficient than the classic Boltzmann machine, where each unit "
"update requires computing inputs from all other units."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:108
msgid "<b>Learning the RBM: Contrastive Divergence Revisited</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:110
msgid ""
"The RBM is trained using the <b>contrastive divergence (CD)</b> algorithm"
" introduced in Section [3.3 Contrastive Divergence](/kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd). The gradient of the "
"log-likelihood retains the same contrastive form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:112
msgid ""
"\\frac{\\partial \\log P(\\mathbf{v})}{\\partial w_{ij}} = \\langle v_i "
"h_j \\rangle_{\\text{data}} - \\langle v_i h_j \\rangle_{\\text{model}}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:114
msgid ""
"Thanks to the conditional independence property of the RBM, the Gibbs "
"sampling steps required by CD become <b>block-parallel</b> operations. A "
"single round-trip consists of sampling all hidden units given the visible"
" layer, then sampling all visible units given the hidden layer. This "
"makes even CD-1 remarkably effective. The weight update for a mini-batch "
"is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:116
msgid ""
"\\Delta \\mathbf{W} = \\eta \\left( \\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{v} "
"\\mathbf{h}^\\top]_{\\text{data}} - \\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{v} "
"\\mathbf{h}^\\top]_{\\text{recon}} \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:118
msgid ""
"with analogous updates for biases. For a full exposition of the CD-k "
"algorithm, refer back to Section [3.3 Contrastive Divergence](/kpp-"
"theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:120
msgid ""
"In practice, <b>CD-1</b>, i.e. k = 1, is often sufficient. The algorithm "
"then becomes remarkably simple: for each data vector, compute hidden "
"probabilities, sample hidden states, reconstruct visible probabilities, "
"sample visible states, recompute hidden probabilities, and update weights"
" based on the difference between the initial and reconstructed pairwise "
"products."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:122
msgid "<b>Free Energy and Marginal Probability</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:124
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"For an RBM, the free energy of a visible vector $\\mathbf{v}$ is defined "
"as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:126
msgid ""
"F_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}) = -\\log \\sum_{\\mathbf{h}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:128
msgid "The marginal probability of a visible vector is then:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:130
msgid ""
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}) = "
"\\frac{\\exp(-F_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}))}{\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}} "
"\\exp(-F_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}))}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:132
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"While the denominator  (partition function over visible states) remains "
"intractable, i.e. still sums over all $2^{N_v}$ visible configurations, "
"the free energy itself is cheap to compute for any given $\\mathbf{v}$. "
"This allows, for example, comparing the relative likelihood of different "
"visible vectors, even though the absolute likelihood remains intractable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:134
msgid "<b>Free Energy and Its Analytical Form</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:136
msgid ""
"In an RBM, the hidden units are conditionally independent given the "
"visible units. This allows us to sum out the hidden units analytically. "
"Substituting the RBM energy function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:138
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = -\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{v} - "
"\\mathbf{c}^\\top \\mathbf{h} - \\mathbf{v}^\\top \\mathbf{W} \\mathbf{h}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:140
msgid "We can sum out the hidden units analytically:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:142
msgid ""
"\\sum_{\\mathbf{h}} \\exp(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})) = "
"\\exp(\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{v}) \\prod_{j=1}^{N_h} \\left( 1 + "
"\\exp(c_j + \\sum_i v_i w_{ij}) \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:144
msgid "Thus, free energy has a closed-form expression:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:146
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"F_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}) = -\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{v} - "
"\\sum_{j=1}^{N_h} \\log \\left( 1 + \\exp\\left( c_j + \\sum_i v_i w_{ij}"
" \\right) \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:148
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>This analytical form is a key computational advantage of the RBM over "
"the classic Boltzmann machine.</b> It allows us to evaluate the relative "
"likelihood of different visible vectors in $O(N_v N_h)$<b> time</b>, "
"without enumerating the $2^{N_h}$ hidden configurations. <del>However, it"
" is important to note that </del><b>the absolute likelihood remains "
"intractable</b><del>, due to the partition function over visible states. "
"Nevertheless, the closed-form free energy enables efficient comparison of"
" relative likelihoods, which is sufficient for many practical "
"applications such as model comparison and sampling.</del>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:150
msgid "Free Energy vs. Expected Energy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:152
msgid ""
"To gain deeper physical intuition, it is instructive to compare the free "
"energy with the <b>expected energy</b> under the conditional distribution"
" of hidden units:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:154
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\mathbb{E}_\\theta[E_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{H}) \\mid "
"\\mathbf{v}] = -\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{v} - \\mathbf{c}^\\top "
"\\mathbf{m}(\\mathbf{v}) - \\mathbf{v}^\\top \\mathbf{W} "
"\\mathbf{m}(\\mathbf{v})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:156
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $m_j(\\mathbf{v}) = \\sigma(c_j + \\sum_i v_i w_{ij})$ is the "
"conditional expectation of hidden unit $j$ given $\\mathbf{v}$. The free "
"energy and expected energy are related by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:158
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"F_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}) = \\mathbb{E}_\\theta[E_\\theta(\\mathbf{v}, "
"\\mathbf{H}) \\mid \\mathbf{v}] - \\text{Entropy}(P_\\theta(\\mathbf{H} "
"\\mid \\mathbf{v}))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:160
msgid ""
"The difference is precisely the <b>entropy </b>of the hidden layer given "
"the visible layer. This aligns with the thermodynamic relation $F = U - "
"TS$: free energy equals the expected energy minus the temperature-"
"weighted entropy. In the RBM, this entropy term accounts for uncertainty "
"in the hidden unit activations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:162
msgid "<b>RBMs as Product of Experts</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:164
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"An RBM can be interpreted as a <b>product of experts</b> (PoE). Each "
"hidden unit $h_j$ acts as an \"expert\" that assigns a probability to a "
"visible vector $\\mathbf{v}$ based on how well $\\mathbf{v}$ matches its "
"preferred pattern (encoded in the weight vector $\\mathbf{w}_{:j}$). The "
"joint distribution is the product of these expert opinions, renormalized:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:166
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{v}) \\propto \\prod_{j=1}^{N_h} \\exp\\left( c_j h_j + \\sum_i"
" v_i w_{ij} h_j \\right) \\bigg|_{h_j \\text{ summed out}}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:168
msgid ""
"The product-of-experts view highlights the RBM's representational power: "
"each hidden unit contributes a soft constraint, and the combination of "
"many such constraints can model complex, high-dimensional distributions. "
"The bipartite restriction prevents experts from directly interacting, "
"forcing them to coordinate only through the visible layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:170
msgid "<b>Variants: Handling Different Data Types</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:172
msgid ""
"The basic RBM with binary visible units is suitable for modeling binary "
"data (e.g., black-and-white images, binary feature vectors). However, the"
" RBM framework extends naturally to other data types by modifying the "
"energy function and the conditional distributions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:174
msgid ""
"<b>Gaussian-Bernoulli RBM</b>: For real-valued data (e.g., grayscale "
"images, continuous features), the visible units are modeled as Gaussian "
"with unit variance (or learned variance). The energy becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:176
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = \\sum_i \\frac{(v_i - b_i)^2}{2\\sigma_i^2}"
" - \\sum_j c_j h_j - \\sum_{i,j} \\frac{v_i}{\\sigma_i} w_{ij} h_j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:177
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The conditional $P(v_i \\mid \\mathbf{h})$ is Gaussian with mean $b_i + "
"\\sigma_i \\sum_{j} w_{ij} h_j$"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:179
msgid ""
"<b>Softmax / Multinomial RBM</b>: For count data or categorical data "
"(e.g., word counts, user ratings), the visible layer can be a softmax "
"unit over a vocabulary or rating scale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:180
msgid ""
"<b>Replicated Softmax RBM</b>: For variable-length documents, the visible"
" layer consists of a set of multinomial units, modeling the distribution "
"of word counts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:182
msgid ""
"These variants preserve the bipartite structure and conditional "
"independence properties, allowing the same efficient block Gibbs sampling"
" and contrastive divergence training."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:184
msgid "<b>Limitations of the RBM</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:186
msgid "Despite its success, the RBM has limitations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:188
msgid ""
"<b>Shallow Architecture</b>: A single RBM is a shallow model with only "
"one layer of latent variables. Its representational power is limited "
"compared to deep architectures, although stacking RBMs to form a <b>Deep "
"Belief Network (DBN)</b> mitigates this (see Section [4.3 Beyond Single "
"Layers: Stacking for Deep Learning](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-"
"theoretical-foundations-bm-deep))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:189
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Partition Function Still Intractable</b>: The marginal likelihood "
"$P(\\mathbf{v})$ still requires summing over all visible configurations. "
"While inference is efficient, model evaluation and comparison remain "
"challenging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:190
msgid ""
"<b>Mode Collapse in CD Training</b>: As noted in Section [3.3 Contrastive"
" Divergence](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-"
"ebms-cd), CD training can suffer from mode collapse, where the model "
"fails to capture all modes of the data distribution. Persistent CD (PCD) "
"improves this but adds computational overhead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:191
msgid ""
"<b>Hyperparameter Sensitivity</b>: The quality of the learned features "
"depends sensitively on the learning rate, momentum, weight decay, and the"
" number of hidden units. Tuning these hyperparameters requires experience"
" and careful validation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:193
msgid "<b>The RBM's Place in Deep Learning History</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:195
msgid ""
"The RBM played a pivotal role in the <b>deep learning renaissance</b> of "
"the mid-2000s. Before the widespread adoption of rectified linear units "
"(ReLUs), batch normalization, and improved optimizers for feedforward "
"networks, training deep neural networks was notoriously difficult. The "
"RBM provided an effective <b>unsupervised pre-training</b> method: by "
"stacking RBMs trained layer by layer, one could initialize a deep network"
" with sensible features extracted from the data distribution, rather than"
" random weights. This pre-training, followed by discriminative fine-"
"tuning with backpropagation, enabled the first successful training of "
"truly deep architectures on challenging tasks like MNIST and later "
"ImageNet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:197
msgid ""
"Although modern deep learning has largely moved away from RBM pre-"
"training in favor of end-to-end supervised training with large labeled "
"datasets, the conceptual contributions of the RBM, i.e. energy-based "
"learning, contrastive divergence, and the power of distributed "
"representations, remain foundational. Moreover, RBMs continue to find "
"niche applications in collaborative filtering, dimensionality reduction, "
"and generative modeling of small-to-medium datasets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:199
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:201
msgid ""
"The <b>Restricted Boltzmann Machine (RBM)</b> imposes a <b>bipartite "
"connectivity</b> constraint: no visible-visible or hidden-hidden "
"connections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:202
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This restriction yields <b>conditional independence</b>: $P(\\mathbf{h} "
"\\mid \\mathbf{v})$ and $P(\\mathbf{v} \\mid \\mathbf{h})$ factorize into"
" products of independent Bernoulli distributions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:203
msgid ""
"<b>Block Gibbs sampling</b> updates entire layers in parallel, "
"dramatically accelerating inference and training."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:204
msgid ""
"The RBM is trained using <b>contrastive divergence (CD)</b> , typically "
"CD-1, which requires only one round-trip of block Gibbs sampling per data"
" point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:205
msgid ""
"The <b>free energy</b> of a visible vector has a closed-form expression, "
"enabling efficient comparison of relative likelihoods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:206
msgid ""
"The RBM can be extended to handle <b>real-valued</b> (Gaussian-Bernoulli "
"RBM) and <b>categorical</b> (Softmax RBM) data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:207
msgid ""
"RBMs served as the building blocks for <b>Deep Belief Networks</b> and "
"played a historic role in enabling unsupervised pre-training for deep "
"neural networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-restricted.md:208
msgid ""
"While no longer the dominant paradigm for supervised deep learning, RBMs "
"remain important models for unsupervised learning, feature extraction, "
"and understanding energy-based generative models."
msgstr ""

